# Comments And Special Markers

- Add comments to explain intent, invariants, lifecycle, protocol shape, trust boundaries, or non-obvious side effects.
- Prefer module-level block comments for non-trivial files and JSDoc for exported functions, classes, and methods whose behavior is not obvious from the signature.
- Do not narrate syntax or restate the code line-by-line.
- Keep comments adjacent to the code they describe and remove or update stale comments during edits.
- If a file already has a clear module doc, extend it instead of adding duplicate overview comments.

## Canonical special comment markers

- `NOTE:` general local context that helps humans and AI read the code faster.
- `WHY:` rationale for a choice that is not obvious from the implementation.
- `INVARIANT:` behavior or state that must remain true across edits.
- `TODO(name/date-or-issue):` planned follow-up with an owner, date, or tracking reference when possible.
- `FIXME:` known incorrect behavior that should be corrected soon.
- `HACK:` intentional workaround; include the removal condition.
- `COMPAT:` browser, protocol, migration, or backward-compatibility behavior.
- `SECURITY:` trust boundary, validation requirement, or secret-handling constraint.
- `PERF:` hot path, cache expectation, batching rule, or latency-sensitive behavior.
- `AI-READ:` rare handoff note for code with hidden contracts or repo-specific traps that are easy to break.

## Editing rules

- Preserve valid special comments when refactoring the behavior they describe.
- Delete special comments that no longer match the code.
- Do not introduce marker spam; one precise comment beats many weak ones.
- Do not add bare `TODO`/`FIXME` comments without enough context to act on them later.
